A [mathematical space](/Mathematics) where the concept of "closeness" is defined, but not necessarily quantifiable with a numerical [distance](/Distance_(mathematics)). This is the essence of a [topological space](/Topological_space). It's built upon a [set](/Set_(mathematics)) of elements, referred to as [points](/Point_(geometry)), and a special structure called a topology. This topology is essentially a collection of [neighbourhoods](/Neighbourhood_(mathematics)) for each point, meticulously crafted to formalize the idea of closeness. While there are multiple ways to define this structure, the most prevalent one relies on the notion of [open sets](/Open_set).

These spaces, in their generality, are the bedrock for defining fundamental mathematical concepts like [limits](/Limit_(mathematics)), [continuity](/Continuous_function_(topology)), and [connectedness](/Connected_space). Think of them as the underlying framework for familiar spaces like [Euclidean spaces](/Euclidean_space), [metric spaces](/Metric_space), and [manifolds](/Manifold). Despite their abstract nature, topological spaces are indispensable, weaving their way through nearly every modern branch of mathematics. The dedicated study of these spaces in isolation is known as [general topology](/General_topology), or sometimes point-set topology.

### History

The seeds of topology were sown surprisingly early. Around 1735, the brilliant [Leonhard Euler](/Leonhard_Euler) stumbled upon a remarkable formula relating the number of vertices (V), edges (E), and faces (F) of a [convex polyhedron](/Convex_polytope), which also applies to [planar graphs](/Planar_graph):



